From Bill Hamilton Subject Re Burden of Proof In article Chris Faehl writes In article ray Bill Ray writes NOTE FOLLOWUPS go to deleted If I make a statement That God exists loves me but in no way insist that you believe it does that place a burden of proof upon If you insist that God doesn't exist does that place a burden of proof upon you I give no proofs I only give testimony to my I will respond to proofs that you attempt to disprove my If you say X statement and give it the authority of fact I will respond by asking you You aren't obligated to say anything but if your intent is to convince me that X statement is true then yes the burden of proof is upon If what was being discussed could be established or disproven by experiment and observation then I would agree with you The burden of proof would belong to But the source document for Christianity the Bible simply assumes God exists and makes it clear to us Calvinists anyway that when a person is in fellowship with God it is because God has taken the initiative in revealing Himself to that So from a Christian point of view the burden of proof belongs to Bill is being consistent with what the Bible teaches in relating his own experience with God but it would be an error on his part to assume that there is a direct causal relationship between his testimony and someone else becoming convinced that God exists and that he needs to be reconciled to If you are merely giving testimony to your beliefs then you are an Please excuse me if I missed an earlier part of this thread in which Bill came across like an What I saw was simply obedience to the scriptural command to always be ready to give a reason for the joy that is in you Bill Hamilton